---

### 2. POSTS AND COMMENTS CRUD OPERATIONS

**POSTS ROUTES:**
- `GET /posts` - List all posts
- `GET /posts/:id` - Get single post by ID
- `POST /posts` - Create new post (requires title & content, userId optional, defaults to 1)
- `PUT /posts/:id` - Update post (title and/or content)
- `DELETE /posts/:id` - Delete post

**COMMENTS ROUTES:**
- `GET /posts/:postId/comments` - List all comments for a specific post
- `GET /comments/:id` - Get single comment by ID
- `POST /posts/:postId/comments` - Create comment on a post (requires body, userId optional, defaults to 1)
- `PUT /comments/:id` - Update comment (body field)
- `DELETE /comments/:id` - Delete comment

---

### 3. DATA STRUCTURES (Type Definitions)

**File: `/src/types.ts`**
```typescript
export interface User {
  id: number;
  username: string;
  email: string;
  password: string;
}

export interface Post {
  id: number;
  title: string;
  content: string;
  userId: number;
  createdAt: string;
}

export interface Comment {
  id: number;
  postId: number;
  userId: number;
  body: string;
  createdAt: string;
}
```

---

### 4. ID GENERATION AND MANAGEMENT

**File: `/src/db.ts` - Helper function:**
```typescript
export function nextId(items: { id: number }[]): number {
  if (items.length === 0) return 1;
  return Math.max(...items.map((item) => item.id)) + 1;
}
```

**How it works:**
- Uses a simple algorithm: finds the maximum existing ID in an array and adds 1
- Called in both posts.ts (line 31) and comments.ts (line 44) when creating new items
- IDs are numeric (integers) and auto-incremented based on existing data
- Each array (posts, comments) maintains its own ID sequence independently

---

### 5. HOW POSTS AND COMMENTS REFERENCE USER IDs

**Posts referencing userId:**
